Wondering what you reassigned him to.

270
00:15:54,200 --> 00:15:57,400
What's it matter, Cain, you jealous?

271
00:15:58,800 --> 00:16:01,200
Yeah, yeah, that must be it.

272
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:25,200
Sorry, Mrs. Carlson,
didn't mean to startle you.

273
00:16:25,200 --> 00:16:28,800
I don't startle easily and it's doctor.

274
00:16:32,800 --> 00:16:35,800
What, uh, what're you looking at?

275
00:16:37,200 --> 00:16:39,000
I don't know.

276
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,400
It's just this last bit
of static that bothers me.

277
00:16:43,400 --> 00:16:45,400
Is there a glitch?

278
00:16:45,400 --> 00:16:48,200
There's a technical
glitch, it just cut out.

279
00:16:48,200 --> 00:16:50,000
There shouldn't be any static.

280
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,800
I've been trying to
access the backup files,

281
00:16:52,800 --> 00:16:53,800
except for no luck.

282
00:16:56,800 --> 00:16:59,000
Maybe I'm just being paranoid.

283
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,600
It's just a bad case of the nerves.

284
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:05,800
Nervous, about being teleported
20,000 light years away?

285
00:17:06,800 --> 00:17:09,000
I'm still trying to wrap
my head around that one.

286
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:12,000
20,000 light years.

287
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:16,200
The very idea just staggers the mind.

288
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:18,600
We are only human.

289
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:20,600
We are none of us machines.

290
00:17:20,600 --> 00:17:22,200
It's okay to be afraid.

291
00:17:22,200 --> 00:17:23,400
It's what keeps us alive.

292
00:17:26,600 --> 00:17:27,400
Cain?

293
00:17:41,600 --> 00:17:42,800
The first transmission?

294
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:48,600
Rations, supplies,
weapons and video equipment.

295
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:51,200
All readings indicate they
made it safe and sound.

296
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:55,600
I've sent a temporary
receiving hub for myself.

297
00:17:55,600 --> 00:17:58,000
I'll set up a permanent
hub when I arrive safely.

298
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
I'll let you know by sending a signal.

299
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,200
When I do that's the all-clear
to start coming through

300
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:05,000
one at a time, in the assigned order.

301
00:18:06,400 --> 00:18:10,000
No signal, no one comes through.

302
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:11,200
Clear?

303
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:12,800
Okay.

304
00:18:12,800 --> 00:18:15,200
We got our atmospheric window.

305
00:18:15,200 --> 00:18:16,000
It's time.

306
00:18:18,200 --> 00:18:21,600
Countdown will start from
five when I hit the launchpad.

307
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:24,000
Good luck.

308
00:18:26,400 --> 00:18:28,800
See you on the other side.

309
00:18:33,200 --> 00:18:35,000
In five, four,

310
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:40,000
three, two, one.

311
00:20:34,200 --> 00:20:36,400
Randall Cain.

312
00:20:48,200 --> 00:20:50,600
When I signed on they
said there'd be travel.

313
00:20:50,600 --> 00:20:53,400
Three, two, one.

314
00:21:00,600 --> 00:21:02,800
How you feeling?

315
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,800
Like a sock that just went
through the tumble dryer.

316
00:21:06,800 --> 00:21:09,600
Give it a sec, you'll feel great.

317
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:11,400
Obviously, we can breathe this stuff.

318
00:21:11,400 --> 00:21:13,600
Yeah, we're acclimated to much worse.

319
00:21:14,800 --> 00:21:16,600
This all the supplies?

320
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:18,600
Carry-ons may shift during flight.

321
00:21:18,600 --> 00:21:20,200
Yeah, obviously.

322
00:21:30,200 --> 00:21:31,000
Damn!

323
00:21:31,800 --> 00:21:32,800
Welcome.

324
00:21:40,400 --> 00:21:42,000
How do I look?

325
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:44,200
You're still ugly.

326
00:21:58,400 --> 00:22:01,400
In five, four, three,

327
00:22:01,400 --> 00:22:06,400
two, one.

328
00:22:23,400 --> 00:22:25,800
Allison Carlson.

329
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:33,800
In five, four, three,

330
00:22:33,800 --> 00:22:38,800
two, one.

331
00:22:57,600 --> 00:22:59,200
In five, four, three,

332
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:05,200
two, one.

333
00:23:13,800 --> 00:23:15,600
In five, four, three,

334
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:21,600
two, one.

335
00:23:34,600 --> 00:23:36,400
Alvarez!

336
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,800
There's a blip
in the teleporter device!

337
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,200
Help me straighten him out!

338
00:23:42,200 --> 00:23:44,000
Don't touch
him, don't touch him!

339
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:45,000
What the hell happened here?

340
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,800
Bone deterioration, his
torso structure is gone.

341
00:23:47,800 --> 00:23:48,600
It's gone!

342
00:23:48,600 --> 00:23:49,800
What do you mean gone?

343
00:23:49,800 --> 00:23:51,400
It just didn't make it through!

344
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:57,400
What was that?

345
00:23:57,400 --> 00:23:58,800
My PDA's gone down.

346
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:00,600
Alright, talk to me, Duncan.

347
00:24:01,800 --> 00:24:03,400
Too much stress on the system.

348
00:24:04,800 --> 00:24:06,000
I warned you about this!

349
00:24:07,200 --> 00:24:08,400
Alright, what does this mean?

350
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:09,600
Where does this leave us?

351
00:24:12,800 --> 00:24:16,200
Well, it means we're on our own.

352
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:33,400
Jesus, what the hell just happened?

353
00:24:33,400 --> 00:24:34,200
Stotzer!

354
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:37,400
Our only mode of transport back to Earth

355
00:24:37,400 --> 00:24:38,600
just turned that guy into hamburger.

356
00:24:38,600 --> 00:24:40,400
How the hell are we gonna get home?

357
00:24:41,400 --> 00:24:44,600
Obviously, his DNA and the
transporter did a disconnect.

358
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:47,600
Now, it's a terrible tragedy, I'm sorry.

359
00:24:48,600 --> 00:24:50,400
But every experiment has its downside.

360
00:24:50,400 --> 00:24:51,400
I'll fix this.

361
00:24:51,400 --> 00:24:52,200
You have my word on it.

362
00:24:52,200 --> 00:24:53,600
Yeah, that's great.

363
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:55,600
That fills me with a
whole lot of confidence.

364
00:24:55,600 --> 00:24:58,600
Alright, alright, we all agree
this is a terrible tragedy.

365
00:24:58,600 --> 00:25:01,200
But let's not forget
what we came here for.

366
00:25:01,200 --> 00:25:02,600
We are currently the first human beings

367
00:25:02,600 --> 00:25:04,200
to set foot on this planet.

368
00:25:04,200 --> 00:25:05,800
Prioritize, people.

369
00:25:05,800 --> 00:25:08,200
Opportunities like this
don't come along every day.

370
00:25:08,200 --> 00:25:12,000
So let's just stay focused on our jobs.

371
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:13,000
He's right.

372
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,000
We're here, we should make the best of it.

373
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:21,400
We're stranded here, aren't we?

374
00:25:21,400 --> 00:25:23,200
Nobody's stranded, darlin'.

375
00:25:23,200 --> 00:25:25,600
It's just a little technical
glitch, that's all.

376
00:25:25,600 --> 00:25:27,800
You call that a technical glitch?

377
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:30,600
It's nothing Duncan can't fix.

378
00:25:31,600 --> 00:25:32,600
Isn't that right?

379
00:25:34,800 --> 00:25:35,800
It'll take time.

380
00:25:39,400 --> 00:25:40,200
Yeah!

381
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:44,600
Here she is.

382
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:48,000
Yo, James!

383
00:25:50,200 --> 00:25:51,000
Business calls.

384
00:25:57,400 --> 00:25:59,000
The camera's working perfectly.

385
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:02,400
Alright, let's get set up.

386
00:26:03,800 --> 00:26:04,800
You ready?

387
00:26:13,600 --> 00:26:15,000
It's the most state of the art camera

388
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:17,800
on the market and nobody else has one.

389
00:26:17,800 --> 00:26:19,200
It's a thousand to one zoom.

390
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:21,400
Let's do this.

391
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:32,800
You ready?

392
00:26:32,800 --> 00:26:34,400
We are rollin'.

393
00:26:36,600 --> 00:26:38,000
I'm James Carlson.

394
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,000
I'm currently standing on Project Oxygen

395
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:43,800
breathing pure, clean air.

396
00:26:43,800 --> 00:26:45,600
Project Oxygen is an unexplored planet

397
00:26:45,600 --> 00:26:48,000
20,000 light years from Earth.

398
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:49,800
How I arrived here and the purpose of

399
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:53,000
this journey will be revealed in due time.

400
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:55,200
But to more immediate business purposes,

401
00:26:55,200 --> 00:26:58,200
I hereby claim Project Oxygen as

402
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:00,800
the sole property of Calron Corporation.

403
00:27:01,800 --> 00:27:02,600
My witness.

404
00:27:04,200 --> 00:27:06,000
Carter Mason, attorney at law.

405
00:27:09,200 --> 00:27:11,600
Do not assume that
what you see around me

406
00:27:11,600 --> 00:27:13,600
is merely another corporate venture.

407
00:27:13,600 --> 00:27:16,800
This pristine, unspoiled world represents

408
00:27:16,800 --> 00:27:19,400
a new beginning for each
and every citizen of Earth.

409
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:23,000
God bless you, God bless us all.

410
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:26,000
That's it.

411
00:27:27,600 --> 00:27:29,400
That sincere?
- Yes.

412
00:27:29,400 --> 00:27:31,000
- Sincere?
- I'd trust you.

413
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:32,600
- Alright, let's go.
- Excellent.

414
00:27:41,400 --> 00:27:43,000
Most of the gear made it through.

415
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:43,800
What do you mean most?

416
00:27:43,800 --> 00:27:45,400
My 4400's toast, man.

417
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:49,600
Two cases of weapons and electronics

418
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:52,200
are missing and there's only two cylinders

419
00:27:52,200 --> 00:27:54,200
for the Magnum, one for the rifle.

420
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:58,400
Two cylinders, six shots
each, for the Magnum.

421
00:27:58,400 --> 00:28:00,600
One, two, three, four, five, six.

422
00:28:00,600 --> 00:28:01,600
Seven shots for the Winchester.

423
00:28:01,600 --> 00:28:04,400
Well, we'll make do.

424
00:28:04,400 --> 00:28:06,200
Vickers and I, 12 each.

425
00:28:07,400 --> 00:28:10,000
We gotta find shelter to
make camp for the night.

426
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:11,600
Stotz, take point this direction, will ya?

427
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:13,200
On it!

428
00:28:14,400 --> 00:28:15,800
Where you headed?

429
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:16,800
I'm taking the point, too.

430
00:28:16,800 --> 00:28:20,400
This is a brand new planet
and I'm a scientist, remember?

431
00:28:21,600 --> 00:28:23,400
You don't leave Stotz's side.

432
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:24,800
Okay.

433
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:28,200
Nutrition, housing, A-okay.

434
00:28:33,200 --> 00:28:34,800
Alright, guys, grab as much cargo

435
00:28:34,800 --> 00:28:36,400
as you can hold and let's roll.

436
00:28:37,200 --> 00:28:39,600
We're already down a man
so you gotta carry extra.

437
00:28:40,800 --> 00:28:43,200
I'm a lawyer, not a pack mule.

438
00:28:43,200 --> 00:28:44,200
Yeah, well now's your chance

439
00:28:44,200 --> 00:28:46,000
to move up in the world, counselor.

440
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:55,200
There's nothing you could do.

441
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:56,400
You know that, right?

442
00:28:56,400 --> 00:28:57,800
I'm the medical officer.

443
00:28:57,800 --> 00:28:59,000
I'm responsible for the life of

444
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:00,800
every person on this expedition.

445
00:29:01,800 --> 00:29:03,600
Well, you didn't design the teleporter.

446
00:29:03,600 --> 00:29:06,400
It was on my watch,
that's all that matters.

447
00:29:06,400 --> 00:29:09,400
Your line of work, I think
you can understand that.

448
00:29:14,600 --> 00:29:16,000
Alright, let's move.

449
00:29:51,600 --> 00:29:53,000
This is amazing.

450
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:58,800
Mature vegetation, clean water, pure air.

451
00:29:58,800 --> 00:30:00,000
That's what Earth must have been like

452
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,400
before man came along
and messed things up.

453
00:30:23,600 --> 00:30:25,800
Ain't it great to
breathe without a mask?

454
00:30:25,800 --> 00:30:26,600
Yeah.

455
00:30:26,600 --> 00:30:28,400
This place is pretty much paradise.

456
00:30:44,200 --> 00:30:45,600
What is it, what happened?

457
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:46,800
I was trailing behind you guys

458
00:30:46,800 --> 00:30:48,800
and I saw something
huge, it was an animal!

459
00:30:48,800 --> 00:30:50,400
Yeah, it must have been big.

460
00:30:50,400 --> 00:30:52,200
And it's damn hungry, too.

461
00:30:54,800 --> 00:30:56,800
Looks like we've made
contact with something.

462
00:30:56,800 --> 00:30:58,800
Yeah, the question is, with what?

463
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:00,000
Alright, let's get outta here.

464
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:01,800
Everybody stick together, go, move!

465
00:31:09,600 --> 00:31:11,400
Gretchen,
what did it look like?

466
00:31:11,400 --> 00:31:13,000
I don't know.

467
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:14,200
It was huge, covered in fur.

468
00:31:14,200 --> 00:31:15,800
I've never seen anything like it.

469
00:31:18,400 --> 00:31:19,400
Everything just happened so quickly.

470
00:31:19,400 --> 00:31:22,400
It grabbed the body and
just dragged it away.

471
00:31:54,800 --> 00:31:56,200
What the hell is that?

472
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:02,600
Something sure did a number on it.

473
00:32:02,600 --> 00:32:04,400
You mean that mother lost the fight?

474
00:32:28,200 --> 00:32:31,400
2.49 meters, crown to toe.

475
00:32:31,400 --> 00:32:32,400
That's a big guy.

476
00:32:32,400 --> 00:32:33,200
Yeah.

477
00:32:33,200 --> 00:32:37,600
Weight, I estimate about 270 kilograms.

478
00:32:38,600 --> 00:32:39,600
Oh, my God.

479
00:32:39,600 --> 00:32:41,000
What?

480
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:42,200
This claw.

481
00:32:42,200 --> 00:32:44,200
The posterior end is soft.

482
00:32:44,200 --> 00:32:45,000
What does that mean?

483
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:48,200
It means that this is a very young bear.

484
00:32:49,400 --> 00:32:51,600
You're telling me this thing's a baby?

485
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:53,800
I'm just as shocked as you.

486
00:32:54,800 --> 00:32:56,400
It's DNA must have undergone some

487
00:32:56,400 --> 00:33:00,400
kind of radical biochemical amplification

488
00:33:00,400 --> 00:33:02,400
including extraordinary growth.

489
00:33:02,400 --> 00:33:04,200
So what are we dealing with?

490
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:09,200
Well, I'm not certain, but
my guess is Ursus spelaeus.

491
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:12,200
It's a prehistoric cave bear.

492
00:33:12,200 --> 00:33:14,800
It's been extinct on Earth
for over 10,000 years.

493
00:33:16,200 --> 00:33:17,400
Bear?

494
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:18,600
No, this is a monster.

495
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:23,000
It was the most formidable
predator in its day.

496
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:25,800
So how does an extinct bear
come to get on this planet?

497
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:30,400
Somehow its DNA sequence regressed.

498
00:33:30,400 --> 00:33:32,800
No modern bear, even full-grown,

499
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:35,800
has claws this big or a hide this dense.

500
00:33:37,200 --> 00:33:40,400
The beast that did this stands 4.5 meters

501
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:42,600
and over 900 kilograms.

502
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:43,800
That's perfect.

503
00:33:43,800 --> 00:33:44,800
So what else?

504
00:33:44,800 --> 00:33:47,200
They're fast, they're tough.

505
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:50,800
They're very smart, lived
and hunted in packs.

506
00:33:50,800 --> 00:33:53,400
Their only known enemy was man.

507
00:33:53,400 --> 00:33:55,400
Over 100,000 years ago
our two species were put

508
00:33:55,400 --> 00:33:57,800
into direct conflict
over food and territory.

509
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:00,200
Man won.

510
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:01,600
Yeah?

511
00:34:01,600 --> 00:34:03,400
Well, I'm not a betting man,

512
00:34:03,400 --> 00:34:05,800
but I don't like our chances in a rematch.

513
00:34:05,800 --> 00:34:08,200
It's one bear, it's dead.

514
00:34:08,200 --> 00:34:09,000
End of story.

515
00:34:11,600 --> 00:34:13,800
We proceed as planned.

516
00:34:13,800 --> 00:34:14,800
Whatever killed this is still

517
00:34:14,800 --> 00:34:16,400
out there so we gotta be careful.

518
00:34:17,400 --> 00:34:19,000
That's why you're here, isn't it?

519
00:34:20,200 --> 00:34:22,600
Good work, trapped on a piece

520
00:34:22,600 --> 00:34:24,400
of rock 20,000 light years from home

521
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:26,400
with carnivores bigger
than my company car.

522
00:34:26,400 --> 00:34:28,200
Duncan'll fix the transporter.

523
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:30,800
You do your job and
keep us alive till then.

524
00:34:30,800 --> 00:34:32,200
Alright?

525
00:34:32,200 --> 00:34:33,000
That's gonna be a bit tough

526
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:36,200
with limited ordinance, don't you think?

527
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:10,000
Okay, as security officer I'm exercising

528
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:12,000
my authority to abort this expedition.

529
00:35:12,800 --> 00:35:14,400
Fine with me.

530
00:35:14,400 --> 00:35:15,800
I don't wanna suddenly find myself

531
00:35:15,800 --> 00:35:17,600
on the bottom of the food chain.

532
00:35:17,600 --> 00:35:19,200
Well, we're not going anywhere

533
00:35:19,200 --> 00:35:20,800
without a working teleport hub.

534
00:35:20,800 --> 00:35:22,200
What happened to the backup?

535
00:35:22,200 --> 00:35:24,800
Obviously, it didn't teleport over.

536
00:35:24,800 --> 00:35:26,200
Yeah.

537
00:35:26,200 --> 00:35:28,800
Well, that should make
Mr. Carlson pretty happy.

538
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:34,000
You think I willingly stranded myself

539
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:37,200
on an alien planet with these prehistoric,

540
00:35:37,200 --> 00:35:38,600
man-eating bears on it?

541
00:35:38,600 --> 00:35:40,400
I think you like your job,

